\begin_layout Chapter
Spaces of functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central objects of study in analysis are functions, and the study of
 sets of functions is what broadly characterizes functional analysis.
 Often, the types of function spaces studied in analysis are 
\emph on
vector spaces 
\emph default
over some field (usually 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{C})$
\end_inset

.
 We have already seen one such space in Chapter 3: the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{1}$
\end_inset

 space or the space of integrable functions.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{1}$
\end_inset

 spaces can be suitably generalized to allow for 
\begin_inset Formula $p-$
\end_inset

th power integrability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:LpSpace"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 be a measure space.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\left[1,\infty\right),$
\end_inset

 the spaces 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}^{p}\left(\X,\F,\mu\right):=\left\{ f\in\measurableFunctions\mid\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert^{p}}<\infty\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

are called 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{p}$
\end_inset

 spaces over 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 we get our original integrable functions.
 We will soon show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{p}$
\end_inset

 spaces are vector spaces; in-fact, they are (semi)-normed vector spaces
 with the (semi)-norm given by the function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pnorm fp:=\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert^{p}}^{\frac{1}{p}}.
\]

\end_inset

It should be clear that the function defined above satisfies the absolute
 homogeneity aspect of norms i.e.
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pnorm{\alpha f}p=\lvert\alpha\rvert\pnorm fp.
\]

\end_inset

However, our function in question fails being positive definite in that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm fp=0\not\implies f=0.$
\end_inset

 In fact, all functions that are almost everywhere equal to zero are mapped
 to zero under this function, which means that it cannot be a bonafide norm.
 Hence, if we can show that the function satisfies the triangle inequality,
 we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{p}$
\end_inset

 is a semi-normed vector space.
 To do this, we will establish a series of results that will be important
 in their own right, but shall also help us get the triangle inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:amGmInequality"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{k}\in\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1},\ldots,\theta_{k}>0$
\end_inset

 be real numbers such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}^{\theta_{i}}\leq\sum_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}\theta_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that since the 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

 function is concave, by induction on the definition of concavity, we have
 that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log\left(\prod_{i=1}^{k}a_{i}^{\theta_{i}}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}\log\left(a_{i}\right)\leq\log\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}a_{i}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{x}$
\end_inset

 is a monotonic function, the inequality is preserved under exponentiation
 which yields are result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
This lemma is often referred to as the inequality between arithmetic and
 geometric means as the right hand side is the standard weighted average
 i.e.
 the arithmetic mean whereas the left hand side is the geometric mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:generalizedHolder"

\end_inset

Let functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\ldots,f_{k}\in\measurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1},\ldots,\theta_{k}>0$
\end_inset

 be real numbers such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}=1.
\]

\end_inset

Then, for any measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lebInt{\mu}{\prod_{i=1}^{k}f_{i}^{\theta_{i}}}\leq\prod_{i=1}^{k}\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}}^{\theta_{i}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}}=0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ 1,\ldots,k\right\} $
\end_inset

 then by Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:intZeroFuncZero"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 almost everywhere, which would imply that the left hand side is identically
 zero.
 This would make the inequality hold trivially.
 Conversely, if any 
\begin_inset Formula $\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}}=\infty$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(f_{i}\right)>0$
\end_inset

 then the right hand side is identically 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 which would again let the inequality hold trivially.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Thus, without loss of generality, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}}<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{i}^{*}=\frac{f_{i}}{\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}}}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}^{*}}=1$
\end_inset

 and moreover if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lebInt{\mu}{\prod_{i=1}^{k}f_{i}^{*\theta_{i}}}=\frac{\lebInt{\mu}{\prod_{i=1}^{k}f_{i}^{\theta_{i}}}}{\prod_{i=1}^{k}\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}}^{\theta_{i}}}\leq\prod_{i=1}^{k}\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}^{*}}^{\theta_{i}}=1
\]

\end_inset

then our claim follows.
 To show this, note that by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:amGmInequality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod_{i=1}^{k}f_{i}^{*\theta_{i}}\leq\sum_{i=1}\theta_{i}f_{i}^{*}
\]

\end_inset

pointwise.
 Integrating both sides, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lebInt{\mu}{\prod_{i=1}^{k}f_{i}^{*\theta_{i}}} & \leq\lebInt{\mu}{\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}f_{i}^{*}}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}\lebInt{\mu}{f_{i}^{*}}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{k}\theta_{i}\\
 & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the first inequality follows from the monotonicty of the integral
 and the first equality from the linearity of integration.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

