\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:innerCauchySchwarz"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(V,\innerproduct{\cdot}{\cdot}\right)$
\end_inset

 be an inner product space.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w\in V$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\innerproduct vw{}^{2}\leq\innerproduct vv\innerproduct ww
\]

\end_inset

and moreover, strict equality holds if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\alpha w$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\R.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The claim is trivially true if either 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $w=0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\innerproduct 0w=0\innerproduct vw$
\end_inset

 by linearity.
 Thus we can assume without loss of generality both are non-zero.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\left(v-\alpha w\right)+\alpha w$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\frac{\innerproduct vw}{\innerproduct ww}.$
\end_inset

 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\innerproduct vv & =\innerproduct{\left(v-\alpha w\right)+\alpha w}{\left(v-\alpha w\right)+\alpha w}\nonumber \\
 & =\innerproduct{v-\alpha w}{v-\alpha w}+2\innerproduct{\alpha w}{v-\alpha w}+\innerproduct{\alpha w}{\alpha w}\label{eq:innerProdExpansion}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the second equality follows from an application of linearity and symmetry.
 Note that the term
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\innerproduct{\alpha w}{v-\alpha w} & =\alpha\innerproduct wv-\alpha^{2}\innerproduct ww\nonumber \\
 & =\alpha\left(\innerproduct vw-\alpha\innerproduct ww\right)\nonumber \\
 & =0.\label{eq:crossProdZero}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Note that equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:innerProdExpansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:crossProdZero"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, together with the definiteness of inner products, imply that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\innerproduct vv & \geq\innerproduct{\alpha w}{\alpha w}\\
 & =\alpha^{2}\innerproduct ww\\
 & =\frac{\innerproduct vw^{2}}{\innerproduct ww}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and rearranging yields the inequality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To see the equality result, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\innerproduct vv=\innerproduct{\alpha w}{\alpha w}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:innerProdExpansion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\innerproduct{v-\alpha w}{v-\alpha w}=0\implies v=\alpha w$
\end_inset

 which shows the necessity.
 To show sufficiency, let 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\beta w$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\in\R$
\end_inset

 and note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\innerproduct vw^{2} & =\innerproduct{\beta w}w^{2}\\
 & =\beta^{2}\innerproduct ww^{2}\\
 & =\beta^{2}\innerproduct ww\innerproduct ww\\
 & =\innerproduct{\beta w}{\beta w}\innerproduct ww\\
 & =\innerproduct vv\innerproduct ww
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second equality follows from linearity in the first argument and
 the fourth equality follows from linearity in both arguments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between inner-products and norms is a tight one; every
 inner-product induces a norm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:normInducedByInnerProd"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(V,\innerproduct{\cdot}{\cdot}\right)$
\end_inset

 be an inner product space and let the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm{\cdot}{}:V\longrightarrow\R$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pnorm v{}=\sqrt{\innerproduct vv}
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Then the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm{\cdot}{}$
\end_inset

 is a norm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that the definiteness condition of norms corresponds to the definiteness
 condition of inner-products, and so is trivially satisfied.
 Next, observe that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pnorm{\alpha v}{} & =\sqrt{\innerproduct{\alpha v}{\alpha v}}\\
 & =\sqrt{\alpha^{2}\innerproduct vv}\\
 & =\lvert\alpha\rvert\pnorm v{}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which gives us absolute homogeneity.
 Finally, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $v,w\in V$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pnorm{v+w}{}^{2} & =\innerproduct{v+w}{v+w}\\
 & =\innerproduct vv+2\innerproduct vw+\innerproduct ww\\
 & \leq\pnorm v{}^{2}+2\pnorm v{}\pnorm w{}+\pnorm w{}^{2}\\
 & =\left(\pnorm v{}+\pnorm w{}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the first inequality follows from the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

